  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which is the best photo editing app for Android and iPhone?",
  "response": "The best photo editing app can vary based on individual needs and preferences, but here are some of the top-rated options for both Android and iPhone:\n\n1. **Adobe Lightroom**:\n   - **Features**: Professional-grade editing tools, presets, RAW editing, and cloud storage.\n   - **Platforms**: Available on both Android and iPhone.\n\n2. **Snapseed**:\n   - **Features**: A wide range of editing tools, filters, and textures, along with the ability to work with RAW files.\n   - **Platforms**: Free on both Android and iPhone.\n\n3. **VSCO**:\n   - **Features**: A variety of filters, advanced camera controls, and social sharing features.\n   - **Platforms**: Available on both Android and iPhone, offers a subscription for additional features.\n\n4. **PicsArt**:\n   - **Features**: Photo editing, collage-making, video editing, and a variety of creative tools.\n   - **Platforms**: Available on both Android and iPhone, with a robust free version and a subscription for premium features.\n\n5. **Canva**:\n   - **Features**: While primarily known for graphic design, it has powerful photo editing tools and templates.\n   - **Platforms**: Available on both Android and iPhone.\n\n6. **Pixlr**:\n   - **Features**: Easy-to-use interface with a variety of filters, overlays, and effects.\n   - **Platforms**: Available on both Android and iPhone.\n\n7. **Afterlight**:\n   - **Features**: Offers a wide range of filters, effects, and advanced editing tools.\n   - **Platforms**: Available on both Android and iPhone, with some features requiring a purchase.\n\n8. **Darkroom**:\n   - **Features**: Destructive and non-destructive editing, RAW support, and a comprehensive set of editing tools.\n   - **Platforms**: Primarily for iPhone and iPad users, with some features available on Android.\n\nEach of these apps has its strengths, so the best choice ultimately depends on your specific editing needs and style.",
